The '''Psi Field''' (ψ) is the real scalar field underlying psionic phenomena. It is generated by coherent neural firing, focused attention, and tuned hardware; it propagates at the speed of light (or slower if it has mass); it carries energy density Ψ ≡ T<sup>00</sup>(ψ); and it couples to electromagnetism and to spacetime curvature.

This page presents the ψ field at the level of the 4D effective theory — its Lagrangian, its stress-energy tensor, the dominant interactions, and the experiential map onto practitioner sensation. For the 5D parent action see [[5D_Action_Principle]]; for the symbol reference see [[Symbol_Glossary]].

This page incorporates the content of the former '''Psi Energy Density Scalar Field''' page (which is now a redirect here). In the historical material, "Ψ" referred to the energy density of ψ — that quantity now lives in §"Energy density Ψ" below.

== Conceptual statement ==

A ψ field is a single real number assigned to every point of spacetime — the same mathematical category as the Higgs field, the inflaton, or the QCD axion. The physics is:

* '''Source.''' Coherent firing patterns in brains, electromagnetic emissions from tuned circuits, and focused attention all act as sources <math>J_\psi</math>.
* '''Propagation.''' Once excited, ψ propagates outward at <math>c</math> (massless case) or with finite range <math>1/m</math> (massive case).
* '''Energy.''' The field carries energy density <math>\Psi = T^{00}(\psi)</math>. Practitioners sense <math>\Psi</math> directly as "energy", "charge", "pressure", or "weight".
* '''Coupling.''' ψ couples to electromagnetism through the factor <math>e^{k\psi}</math> in front of <math>F_{\mu\nu}F^{\mu\nu}</math>, and to gravity through its own stress-energy. Strong sustained ψ therefore produces measurable gravity-like effects.
* '''Self-interaction.''' The <math>\lambda\psi^4</math> term in the Lagrangian (<math>\lambda > 0</math>) stabilises the field and supports [[Soliton_Solutions_of_Psi_Field|soliton solutions]] — self-sustaining localised lumps of ψ.

== Lagrangian density ==

The free-field Lagrangian (no EM, no source) is:

:<math>\mathcal{L}_\psi = \tfrac{1}{2}\,\partial^\mu\psi\,\partial_\mu\psi - \tfrac{1}{2} m^2 \psi^2 - \tfrac{\lambda}{4}\psi^4</math>

Adding the EM coupling and source:

:<math>\mathcal{L} = \tfrac{1}{2}\,\partial^\mu\psi\,\partial_\mu\psi - \tfrac{1}{2} m^2 \psi^2 - \tfrac{\lambda}{4}\psi^4 - \tfrac{1}{4} e^{k\psi} F_{\mu\nu}F^{\mu\nu} + J_\psi\,\psi</math>

The Euler–Lagrange equation gives the master ψ field equation on [[Psionics]]:

:<math>\Box\psi - m^2\psi - \lambda\psi^3 = \alpha\,F_{\mu\nu}F^{\mu\nu} + J_\psi</math>

where <math>\alpha</math> arises from the linear expansion of <math>e^{k\psi}</math>.

== Quantum aspect: the psion ==

The classical ψ field treated above is the coherent-state limit of an
underlying quantum field whose elementary excitation is the
'''[[Psion|psion]]''' - a real, spin-0, self-conjugate scalar boson of
mass <math>m</math>. The relationship is exactly the standard
quantum-optical one between a classical EM wave and its photons: a
ψ configuration with classical amplitude is a coherent superposition

:<math>|\alpha_\mathbf{k}\rangle = e^{-|\alpha|^2/2}\,\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{\alpha^n}{\sqrt{n!}}\,|n_\mathbf{k}\rangle</math>

of arbitrarily many psions populating the same low-momentum mode, with
the practitioner-felt energy density <math>\Psi</math> identified as
the expectation value <math>\langle\alpha_\mathbf{k}|T^{00}_\psi|\alpha_\mathbf{k}\rangle</math>.

This is not a separate "subtle" or "vibrational" entity. The classical
field <math>\psi(x,t)</math> and the psion <math>|\mathbf{k}\rangle</math>
are two descriptions of the same underlying degree of freedom, related
by canonical quantisation.

For the canonical particle definition, quantum numbers, vertex
catalogue, axion comparison, and F1-F11 bounds on the psion's
parameters, see [[Psion]]. For the second-quantised construction
(mode expansion, propagator, Feynman rules) see
[[Quantization_of_the_Psi_Field]].

== Stress-energy tensor ==

By Noether's theorem applied to <math>\mathcal{L}_\psi</math>:

:<math>T^\psi_{\mu\nu} = \partial_\mu\psi\,\partial_\nu\psi - g_{\mu\nu}\,\mathcal{L}_\psi</math>

Component-by-component:

{| class="wikitable"
! Component !! Formula !! Physical meaning
|-
| <math>T^{00}</math> || <math>\tfrac{1}{2}(\partial_t\psi)^2 + \tfrac{1}{2}(\nabla\psi)^2 + \tfrac{1}{2} m^2\psi^2 + \tfrac{\lambda}{4}\psi^4</math> || Energy density <math>\Psi</math> — the directly-felt quantity
|-
| <math>T^{0i}</math> || <math>\partial_t\psi\,\partial^i\psi</math> || Energy flux (ψ-Poynting vector <math>\mathbf{S}_\psi</math>)
|-
| <math>T^{ij}</math> || <math>\partial^i\psi\,\partial^j\psi - \delta^{ij}\mathcal{L}_\psi</math> || ψ-stress / pressure tensor
|}

Source: Standard scalar-field stress-energy; identical structure to Klein–Gordon (Peskin & Schroeder, ''An Introduction to Quantum Field Theory'', §2).

== Energy density Ψ ==

The Psi Energy Density Scalar Field — historically a separate page, now merged here — is the <math>T^{00}</math> component of the ψ-field stress-energy:

:<math>\Psi(\mathbf{x},t) \equiv T^{00}_\psi(\mathbf{x},t) = \tfrac{1}{2}(\partial_t\psi)^2 + \tfrac{1}{2}(\nabla\psi)^2 + \tfrac{1}{2} m^2\psi^2 + \tfrac{\lambda}{4}\psi^4</math>

It is the physical, measurable energy density carried by the ψ field at every point of space and time — '''not''' a separate mystical entity. Practitioners directly experience <math>\Psi</math> as "energy", "charge", "pressure", "heat", or "weight".

In the non-relativistic limit (99% of practical work, <math>\partial_t\psi</math> small):

:<math>\Psi(\mathbf{x},t) \approx \tfrac{1}{2}(\nabla\psi)^2 + \tfrac{1}{2} m^2\psi^2 + \tfrac{\lambda}{4}\psi^4</math>

Physical interpretation of each term:

* '''Kinetic term''' <math>\tfrac{1}{2}(\partial_t\psi)^2</math> — felt as "vibrancy", "tingling", or "pulsing".
* '''Gradient term''' <math>\tfrac{1}{2}(\nabla\psi)^2</math> — felt as directional "push/pull" or "magnetic" quality.
* '''Mass term''' <math>\tfrac{1}{2} m^2\psi^2</math> — inertia and stability of constructs; higher <math>m</math> = denser, heavier feeling.
* '''Interaction term''' <math>\tfrac{\lambda}{4}\psi^4</math> — source of explosive growth in groups and the "burn" of over-extension.

Typical magnitudes for a trained meditator: resting <math>10^{-12}\text{--}10^{-9}\ \mathrm{J/m}^3</math>; peak visible construct <math>10^{-7}\text{--}10^{-5}\ \mathrm{J/m}^3</math>.

